<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: HOW MANY ROLLS OF BUBBLE WRAP? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A small Oregon company has shipped an entire food-processing plant to China. 
Some assembly is required.  
</P>
<P>
 Tech-Mark Inc. President Gildo Martini said his company made a $1.2-million 
dollar deal to sell a ready-to-operate, 7,400-square-foot meat-processing plant 
to a buyer in China.He refused to release the name of the buyer. 
</P>
<P>
 Tech-Mark's manufacturing division will provide the cooking ovens, food 
dryers, steam cabinets and smokehouses.  
</P>
<P>
 Other U.S. manufacturers, working with Tech-Mark, will provide additional 
processing equipment. 
</P>
<P>
 Martini said he sees a wide-open market, at least now, for this kind of 
business opportunity in less technologically advanced nations. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is a growing market that will keep blossoming for years," he said. 
"There is a tremendous need for our equipment in developing countries." 
</P>
<P>
 Tech-Mark puts together packages for sale made by its own manufacturing 
division, Enviro-Pak, and other U.S. companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
