<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: CONTAMINATION FIGHT TARGETS STORM DRAINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MATTHEW MOSK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An effort to prevent Thousand Oaks residents from dumping trash and hazardous 
materials into storm drains will begin this month, city officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 A series of activities that officials say is intended to maintain a clean 
ocean and keep area lakes and creeks free from contamination will begin once 
enough volunteers have come forward to help the program. 
</P>
<P>
 The first project will entail stenciling messages warning "Don't Dump, Drains 
to Lake" onto curbs above storm drains. 
</P>
<P>
 The messages will help remind people that when they pour something down the 
drain, it does not simply disappear, said Mohammad Fatemi, the program 
organizer. 
</P>
<P>
 "Community involvement in this important program will benefit everyone by 
helping to maintain a clean environment," he said. For more information, call 
Fatemi in City Hall at 497-8611. MATTHEW MOSK 
</P>
</TEXT>
