<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE ROLE MODEL; USC'S KEYSHAWN JOHNSON TRIES TO SUCCEED MORTON -- AND IN LIFE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG SANDOVAL and EARL GUSTKEY, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A lot of people are counting on Keyshawn Johnson this season. 
</P>
<P>
 There are the USC football coaches, who believe Johnson could be an 
outstanding replacement for All-American receiver Johnnie Morton. 
</P>
<P>
 There are his teammates, who know that the team's success could be tied to 
Johnson's. 
</P>
<P>
 And, there are those who helped Johnson pull himself out of a morass of drug 
dealing and gang banging. Those are the people he wants to please. 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson is trying to be a role model. He has talked to elementary school 
students about his past and its pitfalls. He has written to high school 
students about not giving up on themselves. 
</P>
<P>
 "I started hanging out with the wrong crowd and got myself in trouble," 
Johnson wrote in Cal-Hi Sports this year. "I was selling drugs, gang banging 
and robbing people on the streets when I was finally arrested in the eighth 
grade and put in a correctional facility for nine months. I didn't do these 
things because I needed money, but because I needed a change of pace." 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson had seemed to be heading in the right direction before he decided to 
change his pace. 
</P>
<P>
 He lived with his mother and brother about a half-mile from USC and, when he 
was 6, found himself on the practice field with Charles White and Dennis 
Thurman and other stars of late-1970s Trojan football. 
</P>
<P>
 He became a regular at practice, asking for wrist bands, retrieving footballs, 
carrying helmets and shoulder pads. 
</P>
<P>
 "The players loved it when I asked if I could carry their pads and helmets," 
he said. "It was after practice and they were tired." 
</P>
<P>
 He was a ballboy for the Trojans for seven years during the coaching regimes 
of John Robinson (on his first tour of duty) and Ted Tollner. 
</P>
<P>
 But when Larry Smith moved in as Trojan coach, Johnson moved to the streets. 
It wasn't long before he found his way to a juvenile detention facility. 
</P>
<P>
 "After I was released from jail, my brothers and sisters sat me down and told 
me that it was time for me to take responsibility for myself," Johnson wrote. 
". . . It was at Dorsey (High School) that I finally found myself. Here I was, 
one of the best athletes in the state and I wasn't preparing myself for 
college." 
</P>
<P>
 In 1991, Johnson was offered a scholarship to Miami but didn't score well 
enough on his SAT. He ended up at West Los Angeles Community College, where he 
struggled with his grades and quit the football team after seven games. 
</P>
<P>
 "He was having a bad year, but we were all having a bad year," said Rob Hager, 
Johnson's coach at West L.A. 
</P>
<P>
 "He sat out a year, took a hard look at reality (and) he took on some 
responsibility. He took inventory of himself, as to what he wanted to do. 
</P>
<P>
 "I never saw him in 1992. When he came back to our program in '93, he had a 
different attitude. He's a mature guy for his years, he's been around." 
</P>
<P>
 The two years that Johnson had dropped out of sports, he said he was learning 
to become a student. 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson bounced back last season with a flourish, scoring 12 touchdowns in 
nine West L.A. games and catching 55 passes for 1,245 yards, an average of 22.6 
yards a catch. 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson has started this season slowly. A thigh bruise has limited his 
practice time, and in Saturday's 24-17 victory over Washington, he caught one 
pass for five yards. 
</P>
<P>
 The bad luck that has followed Johnson on the field, he believes, might also 
be dogging him off it. 
</P>
<P>
 According to court records, a warrant for the arrest of a Keyshawn Johnson was 
issued in 1991 for two counts of misdemeanor theft. The warrant says Johnson is 
accused of stealing a portable telephone valued at $900, and a pager from a Van 
Nuys electronics store. 
</P>
<P>
 It lists Johnson's address as the one he was living at in 1991, and the 
physical description also matches. It also lists the make and model of a car 
that Johnson had at that time. However, the birthdate on the warrant is exactly 
one month and one year off from Johnson's birthdate. 
</P>
<P>
 The Keyshawn Johnson wanted for theft is also wanted for failure to appear on 
five moving violations and driving on a suspended license. USC's Johnson says 
there is a possibility that his driver's license is suspended, but says he no 
longer drives. He also said his driver's license was stolen in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson says he did not know about the warrant until told about it by a Times 
reporter last week. He strongly denies any charges and says it is a case of 
mistaken identity. Johnson is even seeking help to clear his name.  
</P>
<P>
 Police generally do little more than write a report on any misdemeanor crimes. 
The rise in crime in the Southland leaves police virtually no time to 
investigate misdemeanors or to execute those warrants. The warrants are usually 
only served when discovered in traffic stops. 
</P>
<P>
 A USC official said the school also plans to investigate the warrant in the 
hopes of clearing its receiver's name. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 USC has high expectations for Johnson. "He can do all the things Morton could 
do, and he's bigger and faster," receivers coach Mike Sanford said. 
</P>
<P>
 And Hager has no problem comparing Johnson to Morton, who was a first-round 
draft choice of the Detroit Lions. 
</P>
<P>
 "Keyshawn is a phenomenal talent," he said. "He's tall, strong and fast and 
he's got a great eye for the ball. And he likes to compete. It's very 
reasonable to think he can succeed Morton. He's got that kind of talent, and 
Keyshawn won't settle for anything less than that." 
</P>
<P>
 Robinson, Johnson's current coach, echoes that sentiment: "Keyshawn is going 
to be fun to watch. I think he's going to be a dynamic player." 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson wants to be dynamic in other areas, as well. Last June, he talked 
about his background in South Central L.A. at Bixby Elementary School in Long 
Beach. 
</P>
<P>
 "He was sensational," principal Sue Fellenzer said. "He talked about 15 
minutes and he spoke from his heart, with that big Magic Johnson smile. The 
kids not only loved him, but so did the parents." 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson said he talked to the children about "mistakes I made, that they 
shouldn't do what I did." 
</P>
<P>
 He summed up his life this way: "I don't blame anyone for the mistakes I made 
when I was younger. I just want people to know that there is always hope for 
those that have gone astray." 
</P>
<P>
 This is a subject he can discuss from experience. 
</P>
</TEXT>
