<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAUGH LINES; JOKES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In the news: David Letterman, on the presidential candidacy of Dan Quayle: "He 
said that if he loses in '96, he's going to try again in '97." 
</P>
<P>
 Comic Argus Hamilton, on Quayle's candidacy: "Right now he's busy raising 
money for his vice presidential library in Huntington, Ind. It's a four-story 
building but, in Quayle's honor, the elevator doesn't go all the way to the 
top." 
</P>
<P>
 Jay Leno, on the issue of salary caps: "I guess O.J. wants it, but his lawyers 
don't." 
</P>
<P>
 Comedy writer Tony Peyser, on the court ruling that permits women to go 
topless on New York's subways: "The judge also ordered that on cars with more 
than six topless women, there must be a two-drink minimum." 
</P>
<P>
 Comedy writer Bob Mills, on the Air Quality Management District's proposed 
crackdown on restaurant emissions caused by fried foods: "Police officials have 
already notified the agency that officers will refuse to enforce any action 
against doughnut shops." 
</P>
<P>
 Mills, on the Navy retirement pensions awarded Brennan and Olive, the 
underwater reconnaissance dolphins: "They'll each get 750 squid a month." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Celebrity potpourri: Letterman, on Rush Limbaugh: "Earlier today, the New York 
City Police Department announced that if, God forbid, something bad should 
happen to Rush Limbaugh, they would not have enough chalk for a full body 
outline." 
</P>
<P>
 Comedy writer Alan Ray, on Playboy magazine's 40th anniversary: "Hugh Hefner 
can't recall the original centerfolds. He's not too good with faces." 
</P>
<P>
 In a recent Amtrak survey, 1,000 men chose Cindy Crawford as the celebrity 
with whom they would most like to travel. In a related survey, says comedy 
writer Mark Miller, 1,000 women chose a rolling pin as the kitchen implement 
they'd likely use if they found their husbands traveling with Cindy Crawford. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 An old man went into a Catholic Church, entered a confessional and said to the 
priest: "Father, I'm 77 years old, I've been a happily married man for more 
than 50 years and I've never been unfaithful. But yesterday, I made mad, 
passionate love repeatedly to a couple of young, gorgeous women." 
</P>
<P>
 "When was your last confession?" the priest asked. The old man said, "Never." 
The puzzled priest replied, "Then why did you come to confession to tell me 
this?" 
</P>
<P>
 "Because," said the old man, "I'm telling everybody." 
</P>
<P>
 -- Hank Kovell, Beverly Hills 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 When his older son was 10, Ben Hoffman of Monterey Park decided it was time 
for a talk about sex. As Hoffman went from one bit of information to the next, 
the boy looked increasingly upset. 
</P>
<P>
 When I got down to the most detailed part about women, he looked up at me 
pleadingly and said: "Dad, I don't know why you are telling me all this. I just 
want to be a baseball player."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA090694-0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 076506 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
September 6, 1994, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Life & Style; Part E; Page 2; Column 1; View Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
602 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAUGH LINES; IN ARKANSAS, TRY NOT TO SWAT YOUR LUNCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICH TOSCHES, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It's become very popular these days to stereotype all people from Arkansas as 
bug-eating hillbillies. Right off the bat, I must emphasize that such a thing 
is terribly unfair. 
</P>
<P>
 Take the bug-eating thing. 
</P>
<P>
 During the recent Mosquito Cook-Off at Crowley's Ridge State Park in Walcott, 
Ark., not everyone dined on the blood-sucking insects. Only about 100 people 
did. The rest went with the more traditional Arkansas picnic fare -- the 
opossum and provolone Hoagie. 
</P>
<P>
 In the mosquito contest, the big winner thrilled the judges with a 
mouth-watering batch of cookies. Sure chocolate chip is slightly more popular, 
but for crying out loud, chocolate just isn't very good for you. 
</P>
<P>
 The cook-off champion, a guy named Larry -- I don't know if he has two 
brothers named Daryl and Darrell -- starts by crushing the mosquitoes. Crush 
them lightly, he insists, because you sure don't want to be snapping the wings 
off the main ingredient in any recipe. He then scrapes the bugs into a mixture 
of brown sugar and maple syrup. If syrup isn't available, Larry says you can 
substitute crankcase oil from your Uncle Gomer's plow. 
</P>
<P>
 Then he boils the concoction, which he claims rids the bugs of 16 
disease-carrying bacteria. While he admits he's no doctor -- a confession that 
shocked the townsfolk, many of whom had never in 20 years questioned his 
routine demand to "Take off your clothes and cough for me!" -- his explanation 
about cleansing the bugs of disease is good enough for me. 
</P>
<P>
 (Of course, the Menendez brothers' initial explanation that they were only 
skeet shooting and their parents "popped up out of nowhere" was also good 
enough for me.) 
</P>
<P>
 Anyway, when the cookies came out of the oven, people swarmed all over them, 
slapping each other over and over again to get to them because, well, there was 
no longer anything else to do. 
</P>
<P>
 "It tasted good," a 20-year-old resident told the Associated Press, which will 
pretty much cover anything if it's close to one of their bureaus. "You couldn't 
taste the mosquitoes at all." 
</P>
<P>
 You could sense the disappointment in his voice. Apparently he had saddled up 
the mule for the five-mile trip to the park so he could taste the mosquitoes. 
</P>
<P>
 "I coulda' gotten regular cookies at home," he said. He then named about 35 
other things he could have gotten at home, a list that included "drunk" and 
"all covered in slop." 
</P>
<P>
 Other lip-smacking mosquito foods in the contest were mosquito pizza, chili 
with mosquitoes and -- you might want to lean your head real close to the 
toilet bowl before you read this next one -- mosquito meat pie. (Hey, don't say 
I didn't warn you.) 
</P>
<P>
 The idea for the contest came from park rangers who said -- honest to God -- 
that they wanted to get rid of the pesky insects because so many people 
complained about the flying bacteria ranches. 
</P>
<P>
 And in case you were wondering, this was the second annual mosquito cook-off. 
Translated, that means the people had it last year and liked it so much they 
went home that night and danced with the livestock, bless their closely linked 
blood supply. 
</P>
<P>
 And, based on the fact that the mosquito-eating thing was caused by complaints 
about the bugs, I believe we should all fall to our knees right now and pray 
that the people of Arkansas don't start complaining about dog droppings in the 
park. 
</P>
<P>
 Because if they do, and if things follow their usual pattern down there -- 1. 
Define problem. 2. Cook it. -- well, I'm leaving the country. 
</P>
<P>
 OK. So we've cleared up that bug-eating business. Now, about that 
they're-all-hillbillies thing. Nothing could be further from the. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Oops. All out of space. 
</P>
</TEXT>
