8 KILLED IN PLANE CRASHES IN NORTHERN CALIFORNIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Eight people, two of them children, were killed in crashes of light planes at 
two rural Northern California airports Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 Two adults and two children died when the engine on their small plane stalled 
just after takeoff from a small airstrip in the Shelter Cove coastal resort 
area, about 170 miles north of San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
 Witnesses told authorities the plane had just taken off over the ocean when it 
"circled back, then all of a sudden . . . just dropped straight down," said 
Humboldt County Sheriff's Sgt. Wally Williams. 
</P>
<P>
 The aircraft was so badly damaged on impact that neither its make nor the 
identity of the four people on board could be immediately determined, Williams 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 At the Truckee Tahoe Airport, three men and a woman were killed when their 
single-engine plane crashed shortly after takeoff and burst into flames. 
</P>
<P>
 The names of the victims were withheld pending notification of family members. 
Authorities said the men were military personnel. 
</P>
<P>
 Airport spokesman Bill Chilcott said the Cessna 172 had been fueled before it 
crashed Monday morning about 700 feet past the end of the runway. 
</P>
<P>
 The plane ascended only about 60 feet and seemed to veer out of control before 
it hit the ground, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 The crash sparked a small brush fire that was quickly extinguished. 
</P>
<P>
 "The airport emergency teams were out there immediately, but there was no 
chance to save the people on board the plane," Chilcott said. 
</P>
